HEADWORD: Pseudobacteria
<hw>Pseu`do*bac*te"ri*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos>
<ety>[<ets>Pseudo-</ets> + <ets>bacteria</ets>.]</ety>
<fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>Microscopic organic particles, molecular
granules, powdered inorganic substances, etc., which in form, size, and
grouping resemble bacteria.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>The globules which divide and develop in form of chains are
organized beings; when this does not occur, we are dealing with
<xex>pseudobacteria</xex>. <au>Sternberg.</au> </note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1157 --></p>

<p><ent>Pseudoblepsis</ent>⟦br⟧
